INSERT INTO flashcards (course_id, question_text, answer_text, difficulty, order_index) VALUES
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000026', 'What does ADME stand for in pharmacokinetics?', 'ADME describes the journey of a drug through the body: A — Absorption (from site of administration into the bloodstream); D — Distribution (movement from blood to tissues and target sites); M — Metabolism (chemical transformation, primarily in the liver, to facilitate excretion); E — Excretion (elimination from the body, primarily via kidneys in urine). Understanding ADME guides dosing decisions, especially in patients with hepatic or renal impairment.', 2, 26),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000026', 'What is the difference between pharmacokinetics and pharmacodynamics?', 'Pharmacokinetics (PK): what the body does to the drug — absorption, distribution, metabolism, excretion (ADME). Pharmacodynamics (PD): what the drug does to the body — mechanism of action, receptor binding, dose-response relationships, therapeutic and toxic effects. PK determines the drug concentration at the receptor site; PD determines the response to that concentration. Together they inform optimal dosing regimens.', 2, 27),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000026', 'What are the main routes of drug administration and their implications?', 'Oral (PO): convenient, first-pass metabolism, slower onset. Sublingual/buccal: rapid absorption, bypasses first pass. Intravenous (IV): immediate effect, 100% bioavailability, highest risk. Intramuscular (IM): moderate absorption, affected by muscle perfusion. Subcutaneous (SC): slower absorption, suitable for insulin and LMWHs. Inhaled: topical lung effect, systemic absorption varies. Transdermal: sustained delivery, bypasses first pass. Rectal (PR): bypasses partial first-pass, useful when oral route unavailable.', 2, 28),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000026', 'What is bioavailability and the first-pass effect?', 'Bioavailability is the fraction of an administered dose that reaches systemic circulation unchanged. IV drugs have 100% bioavailability. Oral bioavailability is reduced by the first-pass effect — drug absorbed from the gut passes through the portal vein to the liver before entering systemic circulation, where hepatic enzymes may metabolise a significant proportion. Drugs with high first-pass effect (e.g. morphine, GTN, propranolol) require higher oral doses than IV doses or alternative routes.', 2, 29),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000026', 'How do renal and hepatic impairment affect drug dosing?', 'Renal impairment reduces excretion of renally cleared drugs and metabolites — risk of drug accumulation and toxicity. Dose reduction or extended intervals are required for renally excreted drugs (e.g. metformin, low molecular weight heparin, antibiotics). Check eGFR and consult the BNF. Hepatic impairment affects metabolism of hepatically cleared drugs (e.g. opioids, warfarin, benzodiazepines) and may reduce first-pass metabolism, increasing bioavailability. Liver function tests and clinical assessment guide prescribing decisions.', 3, 30),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000026', 'What are narrow therapeutic index (NTI) drugs and give examples?', 'NTI drugs have a small difference between the therapeutic dose and the toxic dose, meaning small changes in concentration can have significant effects. Examples: warfarin (risk of haemorrhage), digoxin (toxicity causes arrhythmias), lithium (neurotoxicity), phenytoin (toxicity causes nystagmus, ataxia, confusion), vancomycin, aminoglycosides (nephrotoxicity, ototoxicity), theophylline, ciclosporin. NTI drugs require therapeutic drug monitoring, dose adjustments based on organ function, and careful attention to interactions.', 3, 31),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000026', 'What is the difference between pharmacokinetic and pharmacodynamic drug interactions?', 'Pharmacokinetic interactions affect ADME: one drug alters the absorption, distribution, metabolism (e.g. CYP450 enzyme induction or inhibition), or excretion of another. Example: rifampicin induces CYP450 and reduces warfarin levels. Pharmacodynamic interactions occur at the site of action: drugs with similar effects combine additively or synergistically (e.g. two CNS depressants causing excessive sedation) or drugs with opposing effects reduce each other''s efficacy (e.g. beta-blocker opposing salbutamol).', 3, 32),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000026', 'What is polypharmacy and what are its associated risks?', 'Polypharmacy is typically defined as the concurrent use of five or more medications, though problematic polypharmacy means using medications where the risks outweigh the benefits. Risks include: increased drug interactions, adverse effects, non-adherence, medication errors, hospitalisation, falls (especially CNS-active drugs), and reduced quality of life. Management: medication review (STOPP/START criteria), deprescribing when appropriate, patient education, and pharmacist involvement. Common in older adults and people with multiple long-term conditions.', 2, 33),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000026', 'How is anticoagulation managed with warfarin, and what monitoring is required?', 'Warfarin is a vitamin K antagonist with a narrow therapeutic index. Monitoring is via the INR (International Normalised Ratio). Target INR: 2–3 for most indications (AF, DVT/PE); 2.5–3.5 for mechanical heart valves. INR checked after dose changes, when interacting drugs are started/stopped, and regularly once stable. Dose adjustments guided by local anticoagulation service or algorithm. Risk of haemorrhage (high INR) and thrombosis (low INR). Direct Oral Anticoagulants (DOACs) do not require routine INR monitoring.', 2, 34),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000026', 'What are the main types of insulin and their onset and duration of action?', 'Rapid-acting (e.g. insulin aspart/lispro): onset 5–15 min, peak 30–90 min, duration 3–5 hours. Short-acting (e.g. Actrapid): onset 30–60 min, peak 2–4 hours, duration 6–8 hours. Intermediate-acting (NPH/isophane): onset 1–2 hours, duration 12–18 hours. Long-acting analogues (e.g. insulin glargine, detemir): onset 1–2 hours, no pronounced peak, duration 18–24+ hours. Mixed insulins: pre-mixed ratios of rapid/short and intermediate-acting. Timing of injection relative to meals is critical.', 2, 35),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000026', 'What are the legal requirements for controlled drug (CD) prescribing and administration?', 'CDs are governed by the Misuse of Drugs Regulations 2001 and the Controlled Drugs (Supervision of Management and Use) Regulations 2013. Prescriptions must include: patient name/address, drug name, form, strength, dose, total quantity in words and figures, prescriber''s signature and address. Administration requires two registered professionals to check. CDs are stored in a locked cupboard within a locked room. Records must be maintained in the CD register (countersigned by two nurses). Discrepancies must be reported immediately.', 3, 36),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000026', 'What are unlicensed and off-label medications and what are the nurse''s responsibilities?', 'Unlicensed medicines have not received marketing authorisation from the MHRA. Off-label use means a licensed medicine is used outside its authorised indication, dose, route, or patient group. Both are legally permissible when clinically justified. The prescriber takes on additional responsibility. Nurses must not administer unlicensed/off-label medicines without a clear prescription and understanding of why it is being used. Document consent where appropriate and ensure access to relevant clinical information.', 3, 37),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000026', 'What is a Patient Group Direction (PGD) and how does it work?', 'A PGD is a written instruction for the supply and/or administration of a named licensed medicine to a specific patient group by specified registered health professionals (including nurses, paramedics, pharmacists). It does not require an individual prescription. PGDs are used for defined situations (e.g. flu vaccination, emergency contraception, travel vaccines). The clinician must read and sign the PGD, assess eligibility for each patient, and document administration. PGDs are approved by a multi-disciplinary group and authorised by the organisation.', 2, 38),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000026', 'What is nurse prescribing and what are the types?', 'Independent nurse prescribers (V300): can prescribe any licensed medicine for any medical condition within their competence, including controlled drugs (since 2012). Supplementary prescribers (V200): prescribe from a Clinical Management Plan agreed with a doctor or dentist for a named patient. Community Practitioner Nurse Prescribers (CPNP/V100): can only prescribe from the Nurse Prescribers'' Formulary for Community Practitioners (basic wound care, laxatives, etc.). All nurse prescribers must complete an approved programme and hold the annotation on their NMC registration.', 2, 39),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000026', 'What are the safety requirements for intravenous drug administration?', 'IV drug administration requires: two registered nurses to check (or nurse and pharmacist per local policy), correct patient identification (five rights: right patient, drug, dose, route, time), aseptic non-touch technique for preparation and administration, knowledge of dilution and infusion rates, compatibility checking (with diluent and co-infused drugs), calculation of rate (use programmable pump where possible), monitoring for adverse reactions during infusion, and documentation. IV drugs have immediate onset — errors can be rapidly fatal.', 3, 40),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000026', 'What is correct subcutaneous and intramuscular injection technique?', 'SC injection: 25–27 gauge needle, 45–90 degree angle, into subcutaneous fat (abdomen, outer thigh, upper arm). Aspirate not required for SC. IM injection: 21–23 gauge needle, 90 degree angle, sites include vastus lateralis (thigh), deltoid (arm), or ventrogluteal (hip). Z-track technique prevents tracking into subcutaneous tissue. Aspirate only required for Z-track technique per local policy. Rotate injection sites. Warm area beforehand for comfort. Document site and patient response.', 2, 41),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000026', 'What are the infusion pump safety concerns highlighted by NRLS incident reports?', 'NRLS (National Reporting and Learning System) reports identify: incorrect pump programming (wrong rate, volume, or concentration), syringe or line selection errors (using wrong pump for drug type), failure to account for dead volume (drug in line not yet delivered), unsecured connections causing air embolism or free flow, alarm fatigue leading to unrecognised occlusion or empty syringe, and use of unfamiliar equipment. Smart pumps with dose error reduction software (DERS) reduce programming errors. Standardised drug concentrations and trained staff are essential.', 3, 42),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000026', 'What is medication reconciliation and when must it occur?', 'Medication reconciliation is the process of comparing a patient''s current medication list against new prescriptions at transitions of care (admission, transfer, discharge) to identify discrepancies, omissions, and errors. It involves obtaining an accurate medication history from multiple sources (patient, carer, GP records, dispensing history), reconciling with prescriptions, and resolving discrepancies with the prescriber. The NICE guideline on medicines optimisation recommends medication reconciliation at every care transition. Pharmacists are key leads in this process.', 2, 43),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000026', 'What are shared care protocols and their purpose?', 'Shared care protocols are agreed arrangements between specialist teams and GPs for prescribing and monitoring of specialist medicines (e.g. methotrexate, lithium, clozapine). They define: which clinician is responsible for each element of prescribing and monitoring, frequency of blood monitoring, what to do if results are abnormal, and when to refer back to the specialist. They ensure safe, uninterrupted supply of specialist medicines in the community and support the GP to manage these safely.', 2, 44),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000026', 'What are the storage requirements for medications?', 'Most oral medicines: store below 25°C in a dry, light-protected environment. Refrigerated medicines (2–8°C): insulin, vaccines, some biologics — check manufacturer guidance. Controlled drugs: locked cupboard within a locked room, keys held by authorised personnel. Flammables: dedicated fire-resistant storage. Eye drops: some require refrigeration, discard 28 days after opening. All medications must be stored in their original containers with labels intact, and stock must be rotated (FIFO — first in, first out). Expired medications must be disposed of per local waste policy.', 2, 45),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000026', 'What are the key considerations for medication management in mental health (antipsychotics and mood stabilisers)?', 'Antipsychotics (e.g. olanzapine, quetiapine, clozapine): metabolic monitoring (weight, blood glucose, lipids), ECG for QTc prolongation, extra-pyramidal side effects (EPSE) monitoring, tardive dyskinesia (long-term). Clozapine: mandatory blood monitoring (neutropenia risk — CPMS/clozapine monitoring service). Lithium: NTI drug, requires regular serum levels (target 0.6–1.0 mmol/L), renal and thyroid monitoring, patient held lithium alert card. All require regular structured medication review and mental health act considerations for capacity and consent.', 3, 46),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000026', 'What is the role of syringe drivers in end-of-life medication management?', 'Continuous subcutaneous infusion (CSCI) via a syringe driver delivers a continuous, consistent dose of medication subcutaneously over 24 hours, avoiding the need for repeated injections. Common drugs: morphine or diamorphine (pain and breathlessness), midazolam (agitation, seizures), hyoscine butylbromide (respiratory secretions), levomepromazine (nausea, agitation). Drugs must be checked for compatibility before mixing. Syringe drivers must be set up and checked by two authorised practitioners. Site changed every 24 hours or if signs of inflammation.', 3, 47),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000026', 'What should patient education on complex medication regimens include?', 'Education should cover: what each medication is for, how and when to take it, common and important side effects to report, what to do if a dose is missed, storage requirements, any food or drink interactions, monitoring requirements (e.g. INR for warfarin), when to seek medical advice urgently. Use teach-back method to confirm understanding. Provide written information (PIL from manufacturer, Medicines Use Review). Involve pharmacist. Consider literacy, language, and cognitive barriers to adherence.', 2, 48),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000026', 'How should medication errors be reported and what is root cause analysis?', 'All medication errors must be reported via the local incident reporting system (e.g. Datix) and to the nurse in charge. Serious harm should be escalated to the duty manager and documented as a Serious Incident (SI). Root cause analysis (RCA) investigates the contributing factors — not just the immediate cause but system failures (inadequate labelling, distractions, staffing levels, training gaps). Individual blame is unhelpful; system improvement prevents recurrence. Share learning at team and organisational level.', 2, 49),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000026', 'What is the Yellow Card scheme and when should nurses use it?', 'The MHRA Yellow Card scheme is the UK''s pharmacovigilance system for reporting suspected adverse drug reactions (ADRs), adverse reactions to vaccines, medical device incidents, and defective medicines. Healthcare professionals and patients can report directly at yellowcard.mhra.gov.uk. Reports should be made for: all ADRs to new medicines (black triangle ▼ drugs), serious or unexpected reactions to established medicines, and ADRs to vaccines. Reports help identify new drug safety signals and protect public health. Nurses are encouraged to report.', 2, 50)
INSERT INTO quiz_questions (course_id, question_text, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_option, explanation) VALUES
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000026', 'What does the ''M'' in the ADME pharmacokinetics model represent?', 'Measurement of drug levels in plasma', 'Metabolism — chemical transformation of a drug, primarily in the liver', 'Mode of drug administration', 'Mechanism of drug action at the receptor', 'B', 'In the ADME model, M stands for Metabolism — the chemical transformation of a drug within the body, predominantly by hepatic enzymes (particularly CYP450 enzymes). Metabolism often converts drugs to inactive metabolites that can be more easily excreted. It is distinct from pharmacodynamics (mechanism of action) and pharmacokinetics measurement.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000026', 'Which of the following is a narrow therapeutic index drug that requires routine plasma level monitoring?', 'Paracetamol', 'Amoxicillin', 'Digoxin', 'Metformin', 'C', 'Digoxin has a narrow therapeutic index — the difference between the therapeutic dose and the toxic dose is small. Plasma level monitoring is required to ensure therapeutic levels and avoid toxicity (which can cause dangerous arrhythmias, nausea, and visual disturbances). Paracetamol, amoxicillin, and metformin do not require routine therapeutic drug monitoring.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000026', 'A patient taking warfarin is started on rifampicin for tuberculosis. What pharmacokinetic interaction should be anticipated?', 'Rifampicin inhibits warfarin metabolism, increasing INR to dangerous levels', 'Rifampicin induces CYP450 enzymes, increasing warfarin metabolism and reducing INR', 'Rifampicin has no effect on warfarin metabolism', 'Rifampicin directly antagonises warfarin at receptor level', 'B', 'Rifampicin is a potent inducer of CYP450 enzymes (particularly CYP2C9), which significantly increases the metabolism of warfarin, reducing plasma warfarin levels and leading to a sub-therapeutic INR with risk of thrombosis. INR must be monitored closely when rifampicin is started or stopped, and warfarin dose adjusted accordingly.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000026', 'A patient on warfarin has a target INR of 2–3 for atrial fibrillation. The INR is checked as 4.8. The patient has no bleeding. What is the most appropriate action?', 'Immediately administer IV vitamin K and admit to hospital', 'Withhold warfarin, recheck INR in 24–48 hours, and reduce the maintenance dose once INR is within range', 'Continue the same dose and recheck INR in one week', 'Stop warfarin permanently and switch to aspirin', 'B', 'An INR of 4.8 without bleeding in a stable patient is managed by withholding warfarin (typically 1–2 doses), rechecking INR, and reducing the maintenance dose once INR returns to the therapeutic range. IV vitamin K is reserved for significant bleeding or very high INR (>8). Stopping warfarin permanently is not warranted without a clinical reason.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000026', 'Which insulin type has no pronounced peak and lasts approximately 18–24+ hours, making it suitable for basal once-daily dosing?', 'Rapid-acting insulin analogue (e.g. insulin aspart)', 'Short-acting insulin (e.g. Actrapid)', 'Intermediate-acting insulin (NPH)', 'Long-acting insulin analogue (e.g. insulin glargine)', 'D', 'Long-acting insulin analogues such as insulin glargine (Lantus) and insulin detemir (Levemir) have a slow, peakless absorption profile lasting 18–24+ hours, making them ideal for once-daily basal (background) insulin dosing. They provide a stable baseline insulin level and are less likely to cause nocturnal hypoglycaemia than intermediate-acting NPH insulin.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000026', 'What is a Patient Group Direction (PGD)?', 'A prescription issued by a doctor for a group of patients on a ward', 'A written instruction allowing named health professionals to supply/administer a medicine to a specific patient group without an individual prescription', 'A framework for nurse prescribers to prescribe any medicine independently', 'A hospital formulary listing approved medicines', 'B', 'A PGD is a formal written instruction that allows specified registered health professionals (e.g. nurses, pharmacists, paramedics) to supply or administer a specific medicine to patients meeting defined criteria, without an individual prescription. The clinician must assess each patient against the PGD criteria before administering. PGDs must be approved by the relevant organisation.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000026', 'Which of the following is the most significant safety concern associated with IV drug administration identified in NRLS incident reports?', 'Incorrect patient identification at the ward level', 'Incorrect pump programming leading to wrong rate, dose, or concentration', 'Failure to document IV drug administration in the medication record', 'Use of the incorrect needle gauge for IV cannula insertion', 'B', 'NRLS incident reports consistently identify incorrect infusion pump programming as the most significant IV drug safety issue, including errors in rate, volume, and drug concentration. Smart pumps with dose error reduction software (DERS) and standardised drug concentrations are recommended mitigations. Human factors such as distraction and unfamiliar equipment contribute.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000026', 'Which of the following BEST describes the risk of polypharmacy in older adults?', 'Polypharmacy is always beneficial as it treats multiple conditions simultaneously', 'Polypharmacy increases the risk of drug interactions, falls, hospitalisation, and non-adherence', 'Polypharmacy only becomes problematic when more than 10 medications are prescribed', 'Polypharmacy risks are limited to cardiovascular medications', 'B', 'Polypharmacy (typically ≥5 medications) carries significant risks in older adults including drug-drug interactions, adverse effects (particularly falls risk from CNS-active and antihypertensive drugs), cognitive impairment, hospitalisation, and non-adherence. Structured medication review using tools such as STOPP/START criteria helps identify inappropriate medications for deprescribing.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000026', 'What additional annotation must appear on an NMC register entry before a nurse can independently prescribe any licensed medicine?', 'Community Practitioner Nurse Prescriber (V100)', 'Nurse Independent Prescriber (V300)', 'Supplementary Prescriber (V200)', 'No annotation is required; all registered nurses can prescribe', 'B', 'Independent nurse prescribers must complete an approved prescribing programme and have the V300 annotation on their NMC registration. This entitles them to independently prescribe any licensed medication (including controlled drugs since 2012) within their area of competence. The V100 is limited to the Community Nurse Prescribers'' Formulary; V200 is supplementary prescribing within a Clinical Management Plan.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000026', 'When should a healthcare professional submit a Yellow Card report to the MHRA?', 'Only when a patient dies due to a medication error', 'When a serious or unexpected adverse drug reaction occurs, particularly for black triangle (▼) or new medicines', 'Only when the prescriber requests a report', 'Only when the patient gives formal written consent to report', 'B', 'Healthcare professionals should submit a Yellow Card report for serious or unexpected adverse drug reactions and for ALL suspected ADRs to new (black triangle ▼) medicines. The MHRA uses these reports to identify new safety signals for approved medicines. Reporting is not limited to deaths and does not require patient consent, though patients and carers can also self-report.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000026', 'What is the first-pass effect and how does it affect oral morphine dosing compared to IV morphine?', 'The first-pass effect increases oral morphine bioavailability compared to IV morphine', 'Oral morphine undergoes first-pass hepatic metabolism, significantly reducing bioavailability — oral doses are typically 2–3 times higher than parenteral doses', 'The first-pass effect has no impact on morphine dosing', 'First-pass metabolism only affects non-opioid analgesics', 'B', 'Morphine is subject to significant first-pass hepatic metabolism when taken orally, reducing bioavailability to approximately 20–40%. As a result, oral morphine doses must be 2–3 times higher than the equivalent IV or SC dose to achieve the same effect. Careful dose conversion is essential when switching between routes to prevent under- or over-dosing.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000026', 'Which statement about controlled drug administration is legally correct in England and Wales?', 'A single registered nurse can administer controlled drugs without a witness', 'Two registered professionals must check and witness CD administration per the Misuse of Drugs Regulations', 'Controlled drugs can be administered without a prescription in an emergency', 'Controlled drug records only need to be maintained monthly', 'B', 'Controlled drug administration requires two registered professionals to check and witness the administration process, with the CD register countersigned by both. This is a legal requirement under the Misuse of Drugs Regulations 2001. CDs must be stored in a locked cupboard and all additions and removals documented in the CD register contemporaneously.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000026', 'What is medication reconciliation and at what point in a patient''s care is it most critical?', 'Checking that a prescription is legible before administration', 'The process of comparing the current medication list with new prescriptions at transitions of care to identify discrepancies', 'Counting medication stock at handover', 'Reviewing medication costs against the drug budget', 'B', 'Medication reconciliation is a structured process at transitions of care (admission, transfer, discharge) that compares a patient''s medication history from multiple sources against prescribed medications to identify and resolve discrepancies, omissions, and errors. NICE medicines optimisation guidance recommends reconciliation at every care transition. It is a high-impact patient safety intervention.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000026', 'A patient is prescribed clozapine for treatment-resistant schizophrenia. What mandatory monitoring is required?', 'Monthly liver function tests only', 'Regular full blood counts via the mandatory clozapine monitoring service due to risk of agranulocytosis', 'Annual ECG and weight check', 'Weekly INR monitoring', 'B', 'Clozapine carries a significant risk of agranulocytosis (potentially fatal reduction in neutrophils). Mandatory full blood count monitoring is required via the Clozapine Patient Monitoring Service (CPMS) — weekly for 18 weeks, fortnightly for one year, then monthly if stable. Clozapine supply is contingent on blood results meeting safety criteria. This is a legal requirement in the UK.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000026', 'When mixing drugs in a syringe driver for end-of-life care, what is the most important safety check?', 'That the syringe is the correct brand', 'That the drugs are compatible with each other in the same syringe and diluent', 'That all drugs are drawn up simultaneously to save time', 'That the syringe driver is set to the maximum possible rate', 'B', 'Compatibility of drugs in a syringe driver is a critical safety check. Some drugs are incompatible when combined (forming precipitates or becoming chemically unstable), which can render medications ineffective or even harmful. Check compatibility using the Palliative Care Formulary or local guidelines before mixing. The most common diluent is water for injection or 0.9% saline, depending on drug combination.')
